Macedonians vote in a referendum to change the country’s name.
The Macedonian people voted on Sunday in a referendum whether to change its name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would settle a decades-long dispute with Greece and have blocked applications for admission to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the majority of Macedonia's Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign raised doubts about whether the result will reach the minimum 50 percent needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the referendum ballot was: “Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?”
Advocates of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to gain admission to entities such as the EU or NATO from Macedonia, one of the emerging countries of the fall of Yugoslavia.
“Today I saw vote for the future of the country, for Macedonia’s youth, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although not legally binding, many members of parliament said they would abide by the outcome of the vote and make it final.
The change from nine would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission stated that at 1 p.m. no irregularities had been registered.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last 2016 parliamentary elections, when 66 percent of registered voters deposited their vote.
“I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, a 62-year-old voter from the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their vote for the Macedonian referendum on the country's name change that would pave the way for its accession to the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018.
In front of parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of tents set up for those who had boycotted the referendum.
“We are in favor of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads up and not through the service door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t accept us as Macedonia, we can go to other countries like China and Russia and join the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I think the overwhelming majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of joining the EU and NATO,” Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be the “confirmation of our future.”
A poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure that is below the required.
Another poll conducted by the Macedonian TV channel Telma indicated that 57 percent of those polled planned to go to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote yes.
For the referendum to be valid, the result must be 50 percent plus one vote.
A failure in the referendum would be the first major blow to the policy of the pro-Western government since it came to power in May.
