"Recovering it is a duty."
In sealess Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile in a bloody 19th century resource conflict remains alive, as does the longing to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
Perhaps those hopes are at their highest point in decades, as Bolivia awaits a decision from the international court of justice on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the necessary momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, expects a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
