North Korea Says No to Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were increasing its mistrust of the United States and that the country would not surrender its nuclear weapons in those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important steps to show its goodwill” last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test camps and committing to the proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see the corresponding response from the U.S.," he added.
"Without confidence in the U.S. there will be no confidence in our national security and, in such circumstances, there will not be unilateral disarmament first on our part."
While Ri resumed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important as it did not reject unilateral denuclearization as had happened with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to “denuclearize” the Korean peninsula while Trump ensured North Korea’s security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first depose its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal of coercion, and even opposes the ‘declaration of an end to war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream for those who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions exacerbate our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the other part of this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to a standstill.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly it was inevitable to strike the United States with North Korean missiles after “evil president” Trump called Kim “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in taking disarmament measures, but said there is still much work to be done and that sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
Trump said there was no deadline for this, and that “it doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three or five months.”
China and Russia are discussing whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “compliance with the Security Council’s sanctions must continue firmly and without exception until we observe full, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would return to visit Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying he had made progress, just hours after North Korea denounced him for making "mafia-like demands".
At a meeting with Moon earlier this month, North Korea vowed to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “corresponding measures.”
He noted that Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he requested were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and the progress towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
This year, a new course at Harvard University is making all its students sleep more in order to combat the growth of the macho culture of studying all night stimulated by caffeine.
One academic found that students at the world’s number one university often don’t know the basics about how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Muller Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact that lack of sleep had on learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you only telling me this now, in my senior year?’
He said no one had talked to him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was launched this year for the first time, explains to students the basics about how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to run the course after discovering that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
An hour-long course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deficiency affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have a right to know this information, in the same way that we have a right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke tobacco," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of the pride of staying up all night still exists, he says, and he adds that modern technology and the growing pressure for students that involved lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you get enough sleep and have a good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he points out. Even avoiding getting fat, since lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which makes him constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm to go to bed, as well as for when they wake up. Likewise, it is recommended that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can unbalance the circadian rhythm and cause trouble sleeping.
