The organization even has Scotland's only and first bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, Estate Manager, says this is the ideal territory for them.
“In Threave we have a great area for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, historic trees and a great habitat.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats yet, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
It highlights the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the properties, since it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest can kill up to 400 females and young, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or harass them, as well as destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
