Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the most recent report by the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Conservation Commission, there is a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the commission, increasingly uneven outcropping conditions are being observed in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which may mean that concentrations are decreasing.
The Red Tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern counties of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Concentrations can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsboro, but in fewer places compared to last week.
The Red Tide was also found in Pasco County.
Mid-level concentrations have been reported on the coast or off the coast of Pinellas County last week, background and elevated concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, background and mid-level concentrations in Charlotte County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of the county.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No such cases have been reported in Northwest Florida over the past week.
